      They should be placed in the same directory as the scripts.

Task 1 - Simple BiLSTM (40 pts)
========================================================================

Architecture: Embedding -> BiLSTM -> Linear -> ELU -> Classifier

Network hyperparameters (fixed by assignment):
    embedding dim = 100
    LSTM layers = 1, hidden dim = 256, dropout = 0.33
    linear output dim = 128, activation = ELU

Training hyperparameters (tuned):
    optimizer = SGD, lr = 0.15, momentum = 0.9
    batch size = 32, epochs = 30
    scheduler = StepLR(step_size=7, gamma=0.5)
    gradient clipping = 5.0

Train:
    python blstm1.py --mode train --data data

Predict (loads saved blstm1.pt):
    python blstm1.py --mode predict --data data

Outputs: blstm1.pt, dev1.out, test1.out

Dev results:
    Precision: 81.69%  Recall: 76.27%  F1: 78.89%


Task 2 - BiLSTM + GloVe + Case Features (60 pts)
========================================================================

Architecture: [WordEmb(GloVe) || CaseEmb] -> BiLSTM -> Linear -> ELU -> Classifier

Same network hyperparameters as Task 1, plus:
    case categories = 6 (pad, lowercase, UPPER, Title, digit, other)
    case embedding dim = 10
    LSTM input dim = 110 (100 word + 10 case)

Training hyperparameters (tuned):
    optimizer = SGD with differential learning rate
        word embedding lr = 0.001 (small, to preserve GloVe)
        other params lr = 0.1
    momentum = 0.9, batch size = 32, epochs = 50
    scheduler = StepLR(step_size=10, gamma=0.5)
    gradient clipping = 5.0

Vocab expansion: dev/test words with GloVe coverage are added to vocab
                  before training (+5331 words, 88.9% -> 91.0% coverage)

Case sensitivity strategy:
    GloVe is case-insensitive, so "Apple" and "apple" share the same
    vector. To keep capitalization info, each word gets a categorical
    case feature (lowercase / UPPERCASE / Titlecase / has_digit / other)
    mapped through a learned 10-dim embedding. This is concatenated with
    the 100-dim GloVe word embedding, giving the LSTM a 110-dim input.
    The word embedding captures meaning, the case embedding captures
    orthographic pattern, so the model can distinguish "Apple" (entity)
    from "apple" (common noun).

Train:
    python blstm2.py --mode train --data data --glove glove.6B.100d

Predict (loads saved blstm2.pt):
    python blstm2.py --mode predict --data data

Outputs: blstm2.pt, dev2.out, test2.out

Dev results:
    Precision: 91.89%  Recall: 93.29%  F1: 92.58%


Bonus - BiLSTM-CNN (10 + 10 pts)
========================================================================

Architecture: [WordEmb(GloVe) || CaseEmb || CharCNN] -> BiLSTM -> Linear -> ELU -> Classifier

Builds on Task 2 by adding a character-level CNN:
    char embedding dim = 30 (required by assignment)
    Conv1d: 50 filters, kernel size = 3, padding = 1
    pooling = max-pool over word length
    LSTM input dim = 160 (100 word + 10 case + 50 char)

All other hyperparameters same as Task 2.

Train:
    python blstm_cnn.py --mode train --data data --glove glove.6B.100d

Predict (loads saved blstm_cnn.pt):
    python blstm_cnn.py --mode predict --data data

Outputs: blstm_cnn.pt, dev_cnn.out, pred

Dev results:
    Precision: 91.59%  Recall: 93.05%  F1: 92.31%


Evaluation
========================================================================

To evaluate predictions against gold-standard dev labels:

    python eval/eval.py -p dev1.out -g data/dev
    python eval/eval.py -p dev2.out -g data/dev
    python eval/eval.py -p dev_cnn.out -g data/dev
